    <!-- Understanding the NBT -->
    <FluentCard>
        <FluentStack Orientation="Orientation.Vertical" VerticalGap="16">
            <h2>Understanding the NBT</h2>
            <FluentDivider />
            <p>
                The National Benchmark Tests assess the academic readiness of first-year university applicants. 
                As an educator, understanding what the tests measure can help you better prepare your students.
            </p>

            <h4>What the NBT Measures:</h4>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Academic Literacy:</strong> Ability to understand and engage with academic texts</li>
                <li><strong>Quantitative Literacy:</strong> Ability to work with numbers and data in context</li>
                <li><strong>Mathematics:</strong> Mathematical competence for STEM programs</li>
            </ul>

            <FluentMessageBar Intent="MessageIntent.Info">
                The NBT complements the NSC - it doesn't replace it. Together, they provide a more complete 
                picture of student readiness for higher education.
            </FluentMessageBar>
        </FluentStack>
    </FluentCard>

    <!-- Advising Students -->
    <FluentCard>
        <FluentStack Orientation="Orientation.Vertical" VerticalGap="16">
            <h2>Advising Your Students</h2>
            <FluentDivider />
            
            <FluentAccordion>
                <FluentAccordionItem Heading="When Should Students Write?" Expanded="true">
                    <p>
                        We recommend students write the NBT in Grade 12, ideally in the first half of the year. 
                        This timing ensures:
                    </p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Results are available for university applications</li>
                        <li>Students can rewrite if needed before final applications</li>
                        <li>Less stress during final exams</li>
                    </ul>
                </FluentAccordionItem>

                <FluentAccordionItem Heading="Which Tests Should Students Write?">
                    <p>This depends on their intended field of study:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>All students:</strong> Academic and Quantitative Literacy (AQL)</li>
                        <li><strong>STEM students:</strong> AQL + Mathematics (MAT)</li>
                        <li><strong>Commerce students:</strong> Usually AQL + MAT (check specific university requirements)</li>
                        <li><strong>Humanities students:</strong> Usually only AQL</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p><em>Always advise students to check specific university requirements.</em></p>
                </FluentAccordionItem>

                <FluentAccordionItem Heading="How Can Students Prepare?">
                    <p>While students cannot "study" for the NBT, they can prepare by:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Reading widely in English - newspapers, academic articles, books</li>
                        <li>Practicing critical thinking and analysis</li>
                        <li>Working with graphs, tables, and data interpretation</li>
                        <li>Reviewing mathematical concepts from Grades 10-12</li>
                        <li>Completing the practice tests available on this website</li>
                    </ul>
                </FluentAccordionItem>

                <FluentAccordionItem Heading="Understanding Results">
                    <p>NBT results are reported in performance bands:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Proficient:</strong> Student demonstrates adequate academic readiness</li>
                        <li><strong>Intermediate:</strong> Student may face challenges; support recommended</li>
                        <li><strong>Basic:</strong> Extended curriculum or foundation program recommended</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>
                        These results help universities provide appropriate placement and support, 
                        not to exclude students from higher education.
                    </p>
                </FluentAccordionItem>
            </FluentAccordion>
        </FluentStack>
